window.docContents[10].resolve({"/Diophantine-Equations-and-Transcendence/Forthcoming-in-mathlib/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Diophantine-Equations-and-Transcendence--Forthcoming-in-mathlib":{"contents":"The node below is an informal statement of a result that is the subject of an open mathlib pull\nrequest (the t-number-theory queue, as of June 2026). It carries a pr_url pointing at the live PR\nand no (lean := …) reference: the declarations are not yet in mathlib v4.30.0-rc2. It connects\ninto the dependency graph through the mathlib-backed transcendence and Diophantine-approximation nodes\nof this chapter via {uses} edges, and should be re-pointed to (lean := …) once the PR merges.\n\n(Gelfond–Schneider theorem, Hilbert's seventh problem.) Let  be algebraic numbers\n() with , , and .\nThen any value of\n\nis transcendental. In particular  (the Gelfond–Schneider constant) and\n are transcendental.The proof is the auxiliary-function method: assuming  algebraic, one builds an\nauxiliary polynomial in  and  that vanishes to high order at many\ninteger points, then derives a contradiction between an arithmetic lower bound on its nonzero\nderivatives and an analytic upper bound — the same tension between good rational/algebraic\napproximation and transcendence that drives Liouville's theorem\n(), with the pigeonhole construction of the auxiliary function\nresting on Diophantine approximation (). PR #35735 formalises the analytic\ncore (non-vanishing and lower bounds for the Gelfond–Schneider auxiliary function; companion PRs\n#33050, #35743, #35744 supply further analytic lemmas).\nIn review — mathlib PR #35735.\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Diophantine Equations and Transcendence","header":"9.8. Forthcoming in mathlib","id":"/Diophantine-Equations-and-Transcendence/Forthcoming-in-mathlib/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Diophantine-Equations-and-Transcendence--Forthcoming-in-mathlib"},"/Diophantine-Equations-and-Transcendence/Newton-polygons-of-p-adic-power-series/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Diophantine-Equations-and-Transcendence--Newton-polygons-of-p-adic-power-series":{"contents":"The nodes in this section are informal: the NewtonPolys project\n(CBirkbeck/NewtonPoly, main branch) is built against\nmathlib v4.28.0-rc1 and therefore carries no (lean := …) reference in this v4.30 chapter. Each node\nrecords the declaration that formalises it, an exact-source permalink at the project's recorded commit\na6d9970, and the true Lean status (the file is sorry-free). The cross-chapter edges to\n and  reflect genuine dependence: the Newton polygon of\na -adic power series is built from the valuation () of its coefficients, and\nits slopes encode the -adic valuations () of the roots. Following Gouvêa\n§7.4, the project abstracts a power series to its valuation sequence and proves the geometric\n\"supporting line\" facts and the radius-of-convergence theorem; the root-distribution functions are\ndefined but the root-counting theorem itself is recorded only as Gouvêa-cited motivation, not as a\nproved statement.\n\nThe valuation sequence of a power series  over a ring equipped with a map\n to  () is the function\n, , with the\nvalue  (encoded ) marking a zero coefficient. The Newton polygon below is computed\nsolely from this sequence; the -adic instance takes \n(). In Lean this is the type\nNewtonPolygon.ValSeq := ℕ → WithTop ℤ, with toValSeq f v extracting it from an actual\nPowerSeries.\nFormalised in NewtonPolys: NewtonPolygon.ValSeq, NewtonPolygon.toValSeq — sorry-free.\n\nLet  be a power series over a field with a non-archimedean valuation\n (). Plot the points  for  and take their lower\nconvex hull: starting from the leftmost point, rotate a line counterclockwise about the current vertex\nuntil it meets the next lattice point, which becomes the new vertex, and repeat. The slopes of the\nsuccessive segments are non-decreasing rationals; the polygon may end in a final ray when the\ninfimum of remaining slopes is not attained at a lattice point. In Lean the result is encoded as a\nNewtonPolygonData record — a list of Segments (each carrying start/end index and valuation) and an\noptional FinalRay — and the rotating-line step is the function nextStep, which at a vertex\n computes the infimum  of the real slope set ()\nand branches on whether it is attained, attained infinitely often, or not attained.\nFormalised in NewtonPolys: NewtonPolygon.NewtonPolygonData, NewtonPolygon.nextStep — sorry-free.\n\nThe Newton polygon () is well-formed and its segments are supporting. A\nNewtonPolygonData is well-formed when consecutive segments share a vertex, segment slopes are\nnon-decreasing, and any final ray's slope is at least the last segment slope; the empty polygon (for\na constant or zero series) is well-formed. Each segment is tight — its right endpoint lies exactly\non the line extending it — and supporting: writing  for the slope set \nfrom a vertex , every later lattice point lies on or above the line of slope ,\n\nFormalised in NewtonPolys: NewtonPolygon.minSlope_supporting, NewtonPolygon.Segment.tight_of_slope, NewtonPolygon.achievingSet_onLine, NewtonPolygon.emptyPolygon_wellFormed — sorry-free.\n\nTightness (Segment.tight_of_slope) is the computation that, with the segment's own slope\n, the value  equals ; it is closed by\nfield_simp; ring after clearing the nonzero denominator . The supporting property\n(minSlope_supporting) is the heart: the real slope to any later point  belongs to the\nslope set , hence is  by csInf_le (using  bounded below); since\n, multiplying through and rearranging by linarith gives ,\nwhich is the infimum characterisation of the slope geometrically. Points achieving the minimum slope\nlie exactly on the line (achievingSet_onLine), the same field_simp; ring computation as\ntightness. Well-formedness of the empty polygon (emptyPolygon_wellFormed) is immediate, all four\nclauses being vacuous. (The project proves these supporting facts about the rotating-line step; it\ndoes not prove that the fully iterated buildNewtonPolygon output is well-formed.)\n\n(Radius of convergence, Gouvêa Lemma 7.4.8.) The Newton polygon () governs\nwhere a -adic power series  converges. Convergence on a closed ball is the\ncondition . Convergence direction: if there is a supporting line\n() of slope  from some vertex  and , then \nconverges on the ball of radius . Divergence direction: if  and infinitely many\ncoefficients lie on a line  through the origin, then  diverges at radius .\nTogether these pin the radius of convergence to  for  the supremum of Newton slopes; for\nthe geometric series  the supremum is  and the radius is .\nFormalised in NewtonPolys: NewtonPolygon.lemma_7_4_8_convergence, NewtonPolygon.lemma_7_4_8_divergence, NewtonPolygon.geometricSeries_radius_of_convergence — sorry-free.\n\nConvergence (lemma_7_4_8_convergence). From the supporting line, \nfor all large  with . For any target , set ; since\n, the linear term  eventually exceeds  (exists_nat_mul_gt), and the\nlower bound then yields  for all large , i.e. .\nDivergence (lemma_7_4_8_divergence). If convergence held at radius  then for \nsome tail has ; but on the cofinal set of indices with  one gets\n (as , ), a contradiction. Combining the two directions across the\nlimiting slope determines the radius ; the geometric-series instance verifies it concretely,\nwith the complementary divergence geometricSeries_diverges_outside showing radius exactly . The\nproject's root-distribution functions (rootCountAtSlope, rootDistribution) record the Gouvêa\ncorrespondence \"a segment of slope  and length  carries  roots of valuation \" as\nthe intended meaning of the data, but that root-counting statement is not itself formalised as a\ntheorem.\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Diophantine Equations and Transcendence","header":"9.7. Newton polygons of p-adic power series","id":"/Diophantine-Equations-and-Transcendence/Newton-polygons-of-p-adic-power-series/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Diophantine-Equations-and-Transcendence--Newton-polygons-of-p-adic-power-series"}});